To create a callback function in React that destroys local storage on logout, you can use the `removeItem()` method of the `localStorage` object. Here's an example:

```jsx
import React from 'react';

function LogoutButton() {
  const handleLogout = () => {
    localStorage.removeItem('user');
    // Other cleanup tasks on logout (if any)
  };

  return (
    <button onClick={handleLogout}>
      Logout
    </button>
  );
}

export default LogoutButton;
```

In this example, the `handleLogout` function is called when the user clicks the "Logout" button. It removes the 'user' item from the local storage using `localStorage.removeItem('user')`.

You can replace `'user'` with the actual key or keys you want to remove from the local storage. Additionally, you can perform any other cleanup tasks you need on the logout within the `handleLogout` function.

In React, you can create a function to check if a user is still logged in and redirect them to a specific URL if they are not. To achieve this, you can use the `useEffect` hook to check the user's login status upon page load. Here's an example:

```jsx
import React, { useEffect } from 'react';
import { useHistory } from 'react-router-dom';

function CheckLoginStatus() {
  const history = useHistory();

  useEffect(() => {
    const isLoggedIn = localStorage.getItem('user');

    if (!isLoggedIn) {
      // If user is not logged in, redirect to a specific URL
      history.push('/login');
    }
  }, [history]);

  return <h1>Checking Login Status...</h1>;
}

export default CheckLoginStatus;
```

In this example, the `CheckLoginStatus` component checks the user's login status by retrieving the `'user'` item from the local storage (`localStorage.getItem('user')`). If the user is not logged in, it redirects them to the `/login` URL using the `history.push()` method from the `useHistory` hook.

You can replace `'/login'` with the desired URL you want to redirect the user to if they are not logged in.

Note: Make sure to wrap this component with a router provider in the parent component for routing to work correctly.

To add a "Remember Me" functionality in your React application, you can store a user's login information in local storage and check it upon page load to keep the user logged in. 

Here's an example of how you can implement the "Remember Me" feature using a callback function in React:

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function Login() {
  const [rememberMe, setRememberMe] = useState(false);
  const [username, setUsername] = useState('');
  const [password, setPassword] = useState('');

  useEffect(() => {
    const storedUsername = localStorage.getItem('username');
    const storedPassword = localStorage.getItem('password');
    const storedRememberMe = localStorage.getItem('rememberMe');

    if (storedUsername && storedPassword && storedRememberMe) {
      setUsername(storedUsername);
      setPassword(storedPassword);
      setRememberMe(true);
    }
  }, []);

  const handleLogin = () => {
    // Handle login logic here

    if (rememberMe) {
      localStorage.setItem('username', username);
      localStorage.setItem('password', password);
      localStorage.setItem('rememberMe', true);
    } else {
      localStorage.removeItem('username');
      localStorage.removeItem('password');
      localStorage.removeItem('rememberMe');
    }
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <input
        type="text"
        value={username}
        onChange={e => setUsername(e.target.value)}
        placeholder="Username"
      />
      <input
        type="password"
        value={password}
        onChange={e => setPassword(e.target.value)}
        placeholder="Password"
      />
      <label>
        <input
          type="checkbox"
          checked={rememberMe}
          onChange={e => setRememberMe(e.target.checked)}
        />
        Remember Me
      </label>
      <button onClick={handleLogin}>Login</button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default Login;
```

In this example, the `rememberMe` state variable is used to track whether the "Remember Me" checkbox is checked or not. Upon login, if the "Remember Me" checkbox is checked, the username, password, and `rememberMe` value are stored in local storage using `localStorage.setItem()`. If it is not checked, the corresponding items are removed from local storage using `localStorage.removeItem()`.

During the component's `useEffect` hook, the stored username, password, and `rememberMe` value are retrieved from local storage using `localStorage.getItem()`. If all the values are present, the respective states are set accordingly to keep the user logged in.

Remember to handle the actual login logic in the `handleLogin` function according to your application's requirements.

To show the date as a reference to the current time in React, you can use the `Date` object to get the current date and time. Here's an example:

```jsx
import React, { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

function DateReference() {
  const [currentDate, setCurrentDate] = useState(new Date());

  useEffect(() => {
    const interval = setInterval(() => {
      setCurrentDate(new Date());
    }, 1000);

    return () => {
      clearInterval(interval);
    };
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      Current Date Reference: {currentDate.toString()}
    </div>
  );
}

export default DateReference;
```

In this example, `currentDate` is a state variable that initially stores the current date and time using `new Date()`. Inside the `useEffect` hook, an interval is set up to update the `currentDate` state every second by calling `new Date()`. The interval is cleared on component unmount to avoid memory leaks.

In the return statement, the `currentDate` state is displayed using the `toString()` method, which converts the date object to a string representation.

This component will continuously display the current date and time as a reference to the current time.

To format the date in a specific format in React, you can use the `toLocaleString()` method of the `Date` object. Here's an example:

```jsx
import React from 'react';

function DateFormatted() {
  const currentDate = new Date();

  const formattedDate = currentDate.toLocaleString('en-US', {
    year: 'numeric',
    month: 'long',
    day: 'numeric',
    hour: 'numeric',
    minute: 'numeric',
    second: 'numeric',
    hour12: true,
  });

  return (
    <div>
      Formatted Date: {formattedDate}
    </div>
  );
}

export default DateFormatted;
```

In this example, `currentDate` is a `Date` object that represents the current date and time. The `toLocaleString()` method is called on `currentDate` with two arguments: the locale and the options object.

In the options object, you can specify the specific parts of the date and time you want to include in the format. In the example, the `year`, `month`, `day`, `hour`, `minute`, and `second` parts are included in the format. You can adjust these options based on your desired format.

The `formattedDate` variable now holds the formatted date as a string based on the specified format. It can be rendered in the component's return statement as needed.

Note: Make sure to adjust the locale and options as necessary to match the desired date format and requirements.

To achieve the desired functionality of showing a modal with an image slider upon button click, you can use HTML, CSS, and JavaScript/jQuery. Here's an example:

HTML:
```html
<button id="openModalButton">Open Modal</button>

<div id="myModal" class="modal">
  <div class="modal-content">
    <span class="close">&times;</span>
    <div class="slider">
      <img src="image1.jpg" alt="Image 1">
      <img src="image2.jpg" alt="Image 2">
      <img src="image3.jpg" alt="Image 3">
