  scroll-snap-align: center;
}
```

JavaScript/jQuery:
```javascript
$("#openModalButton").on("click", function() {
  $("#myModal").fadeIn();
});

$(".close").on("click", function() {
  $("#myModal").fadeOut();
});
```

In this example, when the button with the id `openModalButton` is clicked, the modal with the id `myModal` is displayed using jQuery's `fadeIn()` method. The modal contains a slider section that holds multiple images (image1.jpg, image2.jpg, etc.). The modal can be closed by clicking the close button with the class `close` using jQuery's `fadeOut()` method.

The `slider` class applies scrolling behavior to the image slider inside the modal. You can adjust the styling and the images as needed to match your requirements.

Make sure to link the jQuery library in your HTML file before the custom JavaScript code.

